div.p:
The man looked at him and his hard face softened. Pushing back his tattered cap
                    from his brows he showed his features more openly, and a smile, half shrewd,
                    half kindly, made them suddenly pleasant.

And starting off to walk part of the way back to Weircombe, he sang softly under
                    his breath as he went a verse of ‘Annie Laurie’— 



‘Like dew on the gowan lyin'

Is the fa' o' her fairy feet;

And like winds in simmer sighin'

Her voice is low an' sweet—

Her voice is low an' sweet;

An' she's a' the world to me;

An' for bonnie Annie Laurie

I'd lay me doun and dee!’
